Setting up Kali Linux and Fixing Network Issue

Installed Kali Linux for use in VMWare Workstation, but encountered a network issue

Problem:
Kali Linux VM had no internet connectivity
Ping requests returned "Network unreachable" and no IPv4 address was assigned to network interface

Troubleshooting:
Checked interfaces using 'ip a'
Saw that eth0 and eth1 were up but had no IPv4 address

Solution:
Assigned IP address:
ip addr add 10.0.2.15/24 dev eth0
Set default gateway:
ip route add default via 10.0.2.2
Configured DNS:
nameserver 8.8.8.8 -> /etc/resolv.conf
Implemented permanent fix by installing a DHCP client:
sudo apt install isc-dhcp-client
Then requested an IP:
dhclient eth0
Verified network connectivity by pinging 8.8.8.8

What I learned:
difference between manual network config and DHCP-based configuration
how to assign temporary IP address
how to configure DNS
how to install a DHCP client to fix the issue permanently
how to diagnose network issues using:
ip a
ping
ip route

Tested firewall behavior by allowing and denying port 80

From the Kali machine, pinged the Ubuntu machine:
ping 192.168.56.103

Then, I curled the nginx server:
curl http://192.168.56.103
HTTP requests from Kali reached the nginx server and were logged

Went back to Ubuntu machine and configured the firewall to deny all inbound traffic on port 80:
sudo ufw deny 80

Tried curling again on the Kali machine after, no response was received and no log entry was made

What I learned:
how open ports affect access to a system
how firewalls block traffic before it reaches the application layer
blocked traffic does not appear in logs
how to test service access using curl
how to verify cause and effect when configuring fw rules

Fixed slow APT speeds on Ubuntu

Problem:
Extremely slow apt download speeds compared to kali Linux

Troubleshooting:
APT attempting IPv6 connections that were failing
Default http mirrors causing slow connections in VM

Solution:
Forced IPv4:
sudo nano /etc/apt/apt.conf.d/99force-ipv4
Added:
Acquire::ForceIPv4 "true";
Switched repositories to HTTPS:
sudo nano /etc/apt/sources.list.d/ubuntu.sources
Changed http to https in source links
Reset APT:
sudo apt clean
sudo rm -rf /var/lib/apt/lists*
sudo apt update
APT download speed was much faster after

What I learned:
APT performance heavily depends on mirror and protocol (Kali Linux uses HTTPS by default, no issues on there)
IPv6 can cause slower speeds in VM environments
HTTPS is more reliable than HTTP for package downloads
How to troubleshoot slow package manager behavior

Allowed port 22 on Ubuntu ufw and scanned with nmap from Kali machine

What I did:
Allowed port 22 on Ubuntu ufw
sudo ufw allow 22
Then, scanned the machine's ports using nmap on the Kali machine
nmap (IP address)
Result: saw what ports are open and closed on the Ubuntu machine
PORT     STATE     SERVICE
22/tcp   closed      ssh
80/tcp   open      http


Installed and enabled SSH on Ubuntu

What I did:
After seeing that 22's state was closed on the nmap, realized although I have it set to open on the ufw, I do not have it installed nor enabled
Installed and enabled SSH:
sudo apt install openssh-server
sudo systemctl start ssh
sudo systemctl enable ssh
Verified it's running:
sudo systemctl status ssh
Status was active
Ran nmap again from Kali machine
Result: now that ssh was installed and enabled, port 22 showed as open on nmap
PORT     STATE     SERVICE
22/tcp   open      ssh
80/tcp   open      http
Attempted to connect from Kali using SSH
ssh (username)@(IP address)
Entered wrong password intentionally and verified that the failed authentication attempt appeared in Ubuntu logs
sudo trail -f /var/log/auth.log

What I learned:
Port state depends on whether a service is actually running, not just firewall rules
Allowing a port in ufw does not open it by itself, service must be installed and actively listening on that port
Nmap shows real system behavior
closed = no service listening
open = service is running and reachable
SSH authentication attempts are recorded in /var/log/auth.log and include the source IP and result of login attempt
Relationship between:
service status, port state, scan results, log visibility
Can be used to verify system config and detect unauthorized access attempts
